{
  "answer": "**The term *muʾmin* (مومن, believer)—rendered in the English translation as \"true Believer\" or \"Believer\"—appears only once across the entire *Bang-e-Dara* cycle (Parts 1–3) in the Falsafa corpus.[^1][^2]**\n\nThis single occurrence is in Part 1, poem 38, \"Sayed Ki Loh-e-Turbat\" (\"The Epitaph of the Sayed\"), where a tombstone speaks words of wisdom on leadership, teaching, and statesmanship. The *banda-e-momin* (بندہِ مومن, servant/slave of the believer, i.e., the true believer himself) is described as possessing a heart (*dil*) purified (*paak*) from \"hypocrisy and fear\" (*beem-o-riya se*—likely a poetic compound for moral sickness and ostentation) and standing fearlessly (*be-baak*) before tyrannical power (*quwwat-e-farmaan-rawa*, the commanding authority).[^3]\n\n> To shrink from speaking what you mean is not a worthy trait;  \n> If your intent is noble, why should you fear any fate?  \n> **A true Believer's heart is free of hypocrisy and fear;**  \n> **It stands unflinching when the force of worldly power is near.**[^4]\n\nFor Iqbal, the *muʾmin* thus embodies moral purity, courage, and unflinching resolve against oppression—qualities essential for guiding the community (*qaum*) in a time of spiritual and political revival. This fits Iqbal's broader philosophy of the ideal Muslim as self-realized (*khudi*) and action-oriented, though *Bang-e-Dara* does not elaborate further on the term here. No other poems in Parts 2 or 3 use *muʾmin*/*momin*, \"believer,\" or close synonyms in relevant contexts (e.g., \"faithful\" yields zero results).[^1][^5]\n\n[^1]: *Allama Iqbal, Bang-E-Dara Part 1* (1924), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/38-sayed-ki-loh-e-turbat/translation/#p-c379c6).\n[^2]: Confirmed via exhaustive searches for \"momin,\" \"mu'min,\" \"mumin,\" \"Believer,\" and variants across *Bang-E-Dara* Parts 1–3 English translations/transliterations; no other matches.\n[^3]: Original: بندہ مومن کا دل بيم و ريا سے پاک ہے / قوت فرماں روا کے سامنے بے باک ہے (*Allama Iqbal, Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 38, [original](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/38-sayed-ki-loh-e-turbat/original/#p-d71df3)); transliteration: *Banda-e Momin ka dil beem-o-riya se paak hai / Quwwat-e farmaan-rawa ke saamne be-baak hai* ([transliteration](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/38-sayed-ki-loh-e-turbat/transliteration/#p-b470e6)).\n[^4]: *Allama Iqbal, Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 38, [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/38-sayed-ki-loh-e-turbat/translation/#p-0cf5a4#p-c379c6).\n[^5]: *Bang-E-Dara* Parts 2–3 contain no instances; incidental \"unbelievers\" (kafir) appear in Part 3 (e.g., ch. 8, 20) but contrast with *muʾmin*, not defining it.",
